text.tspan: Risk
Disclosure
Related-Party Transactions
US GAAP considers an equity method investment to be a related party (under ASC 850). An
investment is considered equity method if the owner has "significant influence" over the
investee and typically applies when a company owns 20-50% of the equity. When a relationship
exists where a company exercises significant influence over its customer, there is risk that
transactions may not be conducted at arms length. Related party disclosures allow investors
to evaluate this risk.
MSFT has an equity method investment in OAI*, and NVDA's $100bn commitment will likely
qualify as well. Although MSFT does billions of dollars worth of business with OAI, we have not
seen any related party disclosures.
Furthermore, consideration paid to a customer typically results in a reduction to revenue under
US GAAP (ASC 606). If investors prefer to evaluate revenue this way, better disclosure around
investments in OAI and their timing would allow for this analysis.
Customer Concentration
Compute providers rely on GenAI companies that do not currently generate cash flow for their
revenue growth and return on capex. Lack of disclosure about significant customers leaves
investors guessing. For example, ORCL did not disclose in its 1QFY26 earnings that the vast
majority of its $318bn RPO growth in the quarter came from a $300bn contract with OAI. This
concentration creates significant business risk, as the inability of a key customer to raise cash
would directly pressure top-line growth and cash flow.
Revenue Share Arrangements
It has been reported that MSFT and OAI have entered into revenue sharing arrangements
where each company shares a percentage of their revenue with the other. For example, OAI
may be sharing 20% of ChatGPT revenue with MSFT, and MSFT may be sharing 20% of Copilot
revenue with OAI.
Following this example, it is possible that under US GAAP both companies are reporting 100%
share of the revenue from their own interface plus 20% of the revenue from the revenue share
arrangement (with the cost of the revenue share going through Cost of Goods Sold). This
increases estimates of GenAI monetization for investors that are adding their estimates of AI
revenue across both companies.
MSFT has not disclosed its accounting policy for the revenue share or the amount of these
related party transactions.
Note it is reported that MSFT and OAI revenue share agreements are being renegotiated.
Vendor Financing
In vendor financing agreements a vendor will extend payment terms to its customer so that the
customer has a longer period to pay for its purchases, often charging interest for this service. A
vendor may be more willing to extend payment terms to a customer to support its own sales
than a bank would be willing to underwrite based on the customer's cash flow profile. These
financing arrangements can be concerning if they if they significantly enhance customer
purchasing power and overshoot actual demand.
We are observing the increased use of vendor financing to support cash-strapped customers
with limited disclosure of the terms of these arrangements:
- CRWV discloses "OEM Vendor Financing" of $1.5bn but does not disclose the
counterparty.
- In 2023, NVDA committed to pay CRWV $1.3bn over 4 years to rent back the GPUs it had
supplied to CRWV.
- We see potential vendor support from NVDA to ORCL as ORCL alluded to "better financing
terms from the vendors" on its FY 1Q26 earnings call.
- NVDA's investment in OAI also further supports CRWV and ORCL, which are investing to
build out capacity to sell to OAI.
